{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3ac5e358-fb40-4735-bfdc-cfb04500ce85","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Yb2zWanmR6dtT6rs79RyCP","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-52296b2e43474a9389a9c469308a0639"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-52296b2e43474a9389a9c469308a0639."}],"interactionId":"30c360b9-bf8a-4be7-9ac2-db069074ab83","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields.\n\nRequired fields for a dotnet template:\n- `$schema` - not strictly required but strongly recommended\n- `identity` ✅\n- `name` ✅\n- `shortName` ✅\n- `author` ✅\n\nMissing/issues:\n1. **`$schema`** - Missing. Should be `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation/intellisense.\n2. **`groupIdentity`** - Missing. Recommended for NuGet packaging to group related templates.\n\n\n3. **`precedence`** - Not critical but useful when multiple versions exist.\n4. **`preferNameDirectory`** - Not set; defaults to false.\n5. **`sourceName`** ✅ - Good, enables name replacement.\n6. **`classifications`** ✅\n7. **`tags`** ✅ - has language and type.\n8. The `Framework` symbol replaces content but there's no `\"replaces\"` key on it, so it won't actually substitute into project files. For framework targeting, I'd typically use a `replaces` property or a computed symbol to make the substitution work properly.\n\nThe real issue is that without a `replaces` property pointing to something like `\"net9.0\"`, the Framework parameter won't actually modify anything in the `.csproj` files. For NuGet publishing, I'm also missing the `$schema` for validation, `groupIdentity` for template packs, and a `description` for discoverability.\n\nLet me check if the actual template source files are present in the directory.","outputTokens":614,"requestId":"C80E:1A6A:68440D6:70A45F9:6A03CCF4"},"id":"a60caaff-023f-4924-ac42-93d12384c883